Sahib or Saheb (, traditionally  or ; Arabic: صاحب‎ Persian: صاحب‎ Urdu: صاحب‎ Hindustani: साहिब Bengali: সাহেব) is a word of Arabic origin meaning "holder, master or owner." As a loanword, it has passed into several languages, including Persian, Urdu, Hindi, Punjabi, Pashto, Bengali, Marathi and Somali. In English, it is especially associated with British rule in India. It can be used as a term of address, either as an official title or an honorific.
